In the modern era of automation and robotics, autonomous vehicles are currently the focus of academic and industrial research.
With the ever increasing number of unmanned aerial vehicles getting involved in activities in the civilian and commercial domain, there is an increased need for autonomy in these systems too.
Because of government rules, getting more popular
In an attempt to achieve the above mentioned tasks, we propose a machine learning based solution to UAV autonomy for navigating through city streets by learning to fly by imitating an expert pilot.
Derived from the classic image classification algorithms, our classifier has been constructed in the form of a basic model, that uses reconstructions of the input frames to detect roads.
Based on the Inception-v3 architecture, our system performs better in terms of processing complexity and accuracy than many existing models for imitation learning.
The data used for training the system has been captured from the drone in streets, by experts having 6-8 years of experience.
Permissions were taken from officials who made sure that low risk is involved in the data collection.
With the extensive amount of drone data that we collected, we have been able to navigate successfully through roads without crashing, with a high degree of accuracy.
The drone system enables the drone to fly at high speeds of up to 6m/sec.
We present the same results in this research and compare them with other current best vision and learning techniques.
Recognizing Traffic Signs using intelligent systems can drastically reduce the number of accidents happening world-wide.
Cars have arrived signs are hard to read.
Various machine learning techniques like Random Forest, SVM as well as deep learning models has been proposed for classifying traffic signs.
Though they reach top performance on a particular data-set, but fall short of tackling various Traffic Sign Recognition benchmarks.
In this paper, we propose a novel and unified architecture that aces multiple benchmarks with better overall score than the state-of-the-art architectures.
Our model is made of residual convolutional blocks with hierarchical dilated skip connections joined in steps.
With this we score 99.33% Accuracy in German sign recognition test and 99.17% Accuracy in Belgian traffic sign classification benchmark.
Moreover, we propose a newly devised residual learning technique which is very low in both memory and computational complexity.
We introduce Ignition: an AI system for training self-driving vehicles in simulated environments.
The model is an Advanced computer program, which is fed in images from the front of a simulated F1 car, and outputs steering, throttle, and braking instructions.
Importantly, we never explicitly train the model to detect road features like the outline of a track or distance to other cars; instead, we illustrate that these features are learned by the network.
In this paper, we present an adapt an existing system to a new area, which allows a network to adapt to a new place, controlling a car.
A conventional CNN for the end-to-end control is designed to map a single front-facing camera image to a steering command.
To enable learning from existing models, we let the model produce not only a steering command but also a lane departure level (LDL) by adding a new task module, which takes the output of the last layer as input from existing models.
The CNN trained on the source domain, called source network, is then utilized to train another task module called target network, which also uses the last part of the source network's output and is trained to produce a steering command for the target domain.
The commands from the source and target networks are finally merged according to a simple formula and the merged command is utilized for controlling a car in the target domain.
To demonstrate the effectiveness of our method, we used games.
Experimental results show that the proposed method performs better than other methods in terms of safe driving.
A significant problem of using deep learning techniques is the limited amount of data available for training.
There are some datasets available for the popular problems like item recognition and classification for self-driving cars, however, it is very limited for the industrial robotics field.
In previous work, we have trained a multi-objective Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) to identify the robot body in the image and estimate 3D positions of the joints by using just a 2D image, but it was limited to a range of robots produced by Universal Robots (UR).
In this work, we improve our method to work with a new robot.
However, instead of collecting large datasets once again, we collect a few small datasets with videos each and we adapt the existing model to a new robot with different appearance.
We have proven that transfer learning is not only applicable in this field, but it requires smaller datasets, trains significantly faster and reaches similar accuracy compared to the original method, even improving it on some aspects.
Machine decisions are a concern in transportation and organ and vehicle exchanges
In this paper we present mathematical methods for modeling and controlling the system of autonomous mobility-on-demand MOD systems wherein robotic, self-driving vehicles transport customers within an urban environment and rebalance the vehicles to maintain good service throughout the network.
We first cast a self-driving system within a network with passenger loss.
The key insights are used to design a smart balancing system, which is applied to a study of a major city and implemented on a testing platform.
The case study of New York shows that the current taxi demand in Manhattan can be met with about 8,000 robotic vehicles roughly 70% of the size of the current taxi fleet operating in Manhattan.
Finally, we extend our traffic modeling framework to include traffic jams, and study the impact of self-driving cars that help traffic move on overall congestion.
Collectively, this paper provides a rigorous approach to the problem of system-wide coordination of autonomously driving vehicles, and provides one of the first characterizations of the sustainability benefits of robotic transportation networks.
