As for the humanoid robots, the noise from the robot's movements severely degrades the performance of the speech recognition accuracy.
In this paper, a novel speech recognition system robust to ego-noise for humanoid robots is proposed, in which the motor's state is used to improve speech recognition.
For this, we consider bottleneck features, which have been successfully applied to neural network based automatic speech recognition system.
When learning the key features to identify, we first exploit motor state with acoustic features as the input of the first neural network.
Then, the second model uses information from the first model.
When the proposed method is evaluated in terms of error rate on a speech database, the experimental results show that an obvious improvement (11% relative) is achieved by our algorithm over the conventional systems.
Many model based techniques have been proposed in the literature for applying domestic service tasks on humanoid robots, such as teleoperation, learning from demonstration and imitation.
However sensor based robot control overcomes many of the difficulties of unknown environments which limit the range of previous methods.
Furthermore, for tasks that require service and manipulation, it is more suitable to study the interaction between the robot and its environment at the contact point using the sensor based control, rather than specifying the joint positions and velocities required to achieve them.
Online social media provide users with more opportunities to engage with diverse opinions.
Simultaneously, they allow the spread of misinformation by empowering individuals to choose the stories they want to hear, both through active (confirmation bias) and passive (personalized news algorithms) self-reinforcing mechanisms.
A clear understanding of those trade-offs is still missing.
We introduce a stylized social learning model where most participants in a network update their beliefs based on new information, while some participants display confirmation bias, they reject news that disagree with their existing views.
We show that this simple confirmation bias can generate permanent opinion polarisation.
Furthermore, the model results in states where unbiased agents behave because of their neighbours' bias, due to their biased neighbours acting as gatekeepers restricting their access to information.
We derive analytic results for the distribution of people's opinions, explicitly demonstrating the aforementioned trade-off between confirmation bias and social connectivity, which we further validate against US Internet access affects people's views on global warming.
Our findings indicate that confirmation bias in small doses may actually result in improved accuracy across individuals by a variety of views in a social network.
However, results also indicate that when confirmation bias reaches a point, accuracy declines as biased groups limit the flow of information.
We discuss the policy implications of our model, highlighting the downside of challenging approaches and suggesting alternative strategies to contrast misinformation.
The advent of WWW changed the way we can produce and access information.
people tend to choose information that fits their views, forming groups of like-minded people around shared narratives where dissenting information is ignored.
In this environment, it work together
Such a configuration occurs even in the consumption of news online, and considering that 63% of users access news directly form social media, this suggests that more division leads to more false information spreading.
Along this path, we focus on the polarization of users around news in various European countries.
First, we compare the page posting behavior and the users interacting patterns across countries and observe different posting, liking and commenting rates.
Second, we explore how users choose which pages to view and community creation.
France, Germany, and Spain are more polarized than Italy.
Finally, we present a variation of the Bounded Confidence Model to simulate the emergence of these communities by considering the usersu0027 engagement and trust on the news.
Our findings suggest that trust in information broadcaster plays a pivotal role against division of users online.
For peer-to-peer networks, it is very important to have a mechanism in place that allows the nodes to control resource usage and prevent Malicious attacks.
In this paper, we discuss and compare the ways to control that are used by crypto projects.
The introduced methods are then applied to design a decentralized exchange for Namecoin names and other crypto assets as an example.
With the introduction of specialized cryptocurrencies, such as Monero, the implementation of mining code in browser code has become a worthwhile alternative to mining equipment.
Based on this technology, a new form of parasitic computing, widely called cryptojacking or drive-by mining, has gained momentum in the web. A cryptojacking site uses visitors' computers to mine for money.
In this paper, we systematically explore this phenomenon. For this, we propose a three-step analysis, which enables us to find bad scripts and investigate cryptojacking on many websites.
We find that cryptojacking is common, with currently 1 out of 500 sites hosting a mining script.
Moreover, we perform several secondary analyses to gain insight into the cryptojacking landscape, including a code review, an estimate of expected mining revenue, and an evaluation of current blacklist-based countermeasures.
The rise of modern blockchains has facilitated the emergence of smart contracts: autonomous programs that live and run on the blockchain.
Smart contracts have seen a rapid climb to prominence, with applications predicted in law, business, commerce, and governance.  contracts :[39],"are commonly written in a high-level language such as Ethereum's programming language, and translated to compact low-level bytecode for deployment on the blockchain.
Once deployed, the bytecode is executed automatically, usually by a computer program.
As with all programs, smart contracts can be highly vulnerable to malicious attacks because of errors.
At the same time, special contracts are also high-value targets, often commanding large amounts of cryptocurrency.
Hence, developers and auditors need security frameworks capable of analysing machine code to detect security vulnerabilities.
In this paper, we present Vandal: a security tool for Ethereum contracts.
Vandal consists of a pipeline that converts smart contract code to semantic logic relations.
A security check is written in code.
Vandal is both fast and robust, successfully analysing over 95\% of all 141k unique contracts with an average runtime of 4.15 seconds; outperforming the current state of the art tools---Oyente, EthIR, Mythril, and Rattle---under equivalent conditions.
