As research has shown people are affected by various biases in their decisions.
In our paper we study the impact of biases on managers on team performance.
In the simulations, managerial decisions which are based on various levels of complexity and different incentive systems suffer from biases known from basic decision-making theory.
The results illustrate how biases in combination with each other and in different organizational contexts affect organizational performance.
We find that, contrary to intuition, different types of biases significantly improve organizational performance while these biases negatively affect organizational performance when they occur separately.
This might raise questions if decisions should be rational.
Perception of the local environment is a precondition for mobile robots to navigate safely.
Most robots rely on planar regions. small robots and humanoids
For humanoids, a simple 2D occupancy map as environment representation on which a path is planned is hereby not sufficient since they can step over and onto objects and therefore need height information.
Considering dynamic obstacles introduces another level of complexity, since they can lead to necessary replanning or collisions at later stages.
In this paper, we present a framework that first extracts planar regions in height maps and detects dynamic obstacles.
Our system then uses this information to create maps, where paths are quick.
We show in actual tests that our framework keeps run times well under 10ms for one single cycle and allows for real-time footstep planning.
A service robot often first has to search for a user to carry out a desired task.
This is a challenging problem, especially when this person moves around since the robot’s field of view is constrained and the environment structure typically poses further visibility constraints that influence the perception of the user.
In this paper, we propose a novel method that computes the likelihood of the user’s observability at each possible location in the environment based on Monte Carlo simulations.
As the robot needs time to reach the search locations, we take this time as well as the visibility limitations into account when computing search locations.
The robot chooses the next location.
Our experiments in real-world situations demonstrate that our approach leads to a significantly shorter search time compared to a greedy approach with background information.
People walk on usual paths between those places by a mobile robot.
Depending on the environment, following a human's steps might not be the optimal solution since more efficient routes for the robot are available.
We propose to perform a prediction about the human's future movements and use this information in a reinforcement learning framework to generate foresighted navigation actions for the robot.
human will often be blocked from view because of obstacles, it's hard to know where the person is.
Our approach deals with such situations by taking into account when objects block the robot's view such that the robot automatically considers to execute actions to get the human in its field of view.
We show in actual experiments that our technique leads to much shorter paths compared to a robot following the user.
In this paper, we introduce an approach to efficient robot navigation through cluttered indoor environments.
We propose to estimate local obstacle densities based on detected objects and use them to predict traversal costs corresponding to potential obstacles in regions not yet observable by the robot's sensors.
By taking into account the costs for the path, the robot is then able to navigate more efficiently and reduces the risk of getting stuck in cluttered regions.
As the experimental results demonstrate, our method enables the robot to efficiently navigate through environments containing cluttered spaces and achieves significantly shorter times compared to a standard approach not using any prediction.
In this paper, we present a navigation system that allows humanoid robots to autonomously navigate in cluttered spaces.
From the data of an onboard depth camera, the system determines the robot's location to correct its movement and maintains a heightmap representation of the environment.
Based on this model, our system takes actions, leading the robot to target locations.
To efficiently check for collisions, we developed a new approach that takes into consideration the robot's shape and the obstacles.
As we demonstrate in experiments with a Nao humanoid, our system makes navigation easier and the robot can handle hard terrain.
In this paper, we present a new method to accurately calibrate the kinematic model of a humanoid based on observations of its monocular camera.
Our technique estimates the parameters of the complete model, consisting of the body angles, as well as the camera extrinsic and intrinsic parameters.
Furthermore, we developed an approach to automatically select a subset of configurations for the calibration process that yields a good trade-off between the number of observations and accuracy.
Our method is better
Hence, our system only requires a reduced number of configurations to achieve accurate results.
Our optimization is general and can be applied to robots
