A key problem for cars with no driver is the understanding, of the current driving situation.
Addressing this issue requires the extraction of meaningful information from on-board stereo imagery by classifying the fundamental elements of urban scenes into categories that can more easily be interpreted and be reflected upon (streets, buildings, pedestrians, vehicles, signs, etc.).
A method is proposed to combine 3D maps with images and 3D maps.
A novel fusion architecture based on the Stixel framework is presented for combining per-pixel segmentation with depth information obtained from stereo imagery while integrating coarse prior depth and label information.
the approach was tested on a manually labeled data set in urban environments
The results show that the classification accuracy was much improved by this method compared to what is obtained from pixel-wise segmentation of the CNN alone.
In recent years self-driving cars have become more commonplace on public roads, with the promise of bringing safety and efficiency to modern transportation systems.
Increasing the reliability of these vehicles on the road requires an extensive suite of software tests, ideally performed on realistic computer simulations, where multiple vehicles and pedestrians interact with the self-driving vehicle.
It is therefore of critical importance to ensure that self-driving software is assessed against a wide range of challenging simulated driving scenarios.
The current state, as adopted by some of the leaders in self-driving cars, still relies on human input [1].
In this paper we propose to automate the process using machine learning optimization to generate adversarial self-driving scenarios that expose poorly-engineered or poorly-trained self-driving policies, and increase the risk of collision with simulated pedestrians and vehicles.
We show that by incorporating the generated scenarios into the training set of the self-driving policy, and by fine-tuning the policy using vision-based imitation learning we obtain safer self-driving behavior.
With the developing of the technology on self-driving, more and more L3 driverless vehicles are launched in market, people get opportunities to experience the self-driving cars in their daily life.
As a result, there is a growing demand for the autopilot experience.
Natural and efficient human-computer interaction can not only improve the driving experience, but also accelerate the process of self-driving commercialization.
This paper discusses eye movement, voice commands and hand gestures in self-driving cars, and analyzes the technology, advantages and disadvantages of the existing interaction modes, and prospect the future development trend of self-driving human-computer interaction.
Self-driving vehicle technologies are progressing rapidly and are expected to play a significant role in the future of transportation.
One of the main challenges for self-driving vehicles on public roads is the safe cooperation among vehicles using sensor-based perception and inter-vehicle communications.
When self-driving vehicles try to occupy the same space, they might collide with each other, might get blocked, or might brake hard making it uncomfortable or unsafe for passengers in a self-driving vehicle.
In this paper, we study how a self-driving car can safely navigate merge points, where two lanes with different traffic rules meet.
We present a safe protocol for merge points named Safe Merge System, where driving cars use sensors and communication to work with other cars.
Our simulation results show that our traffic protocol has higher traffic throughput, compared to basic traffic rules, while ensuring safety.
