The focus of the 1-8 hours after exercise is to enhance processes that help the body recover.
Recommended nutritional strategies to maximize recovery in skeletal muscle include protein for enhancing rates of protein synthesis and carbohydrate for replenishing glycogen stores [2],[3].
Eating protein after exercise helps activate two responses that work together at muscle growth to stimulate increasing muscle protein synthesis [4]–[6].
Eating 20-25 grams of high-quality protein after exercise [7], repeated every 4 h [8] has been shown to maximise the anabolic response in skeletal muscle.
The cultural environment surrounding some sports often involves the intake of large amounts of alcohol after training and competition, in team sports, heavy drinking is a particular risk.
The outcomes of binge drinking after exercise are likely to include the effect of alcohol on the body as well as the indirect effect on the athlete's recovery due to not eating or resting due to being drunk.
Although the concurrent consumption of carbohydrate can partially offset the deleterious effects of alcohol intake on post-exercise glycogen resynthesis [14], the effect of drinking on muscle protein.
The aim of the current study was to determine the effect of alcohol intake on cell signaling and muscle protein synthesis in humans during recovery from a bout of strenuous exercise approximating stresses an athlete may experience in training and performance for various team sports such as various football and rugby codes, and court sports.
We hypothesized that compared to post-exercise protein intake, co-ingestion of alcohol would slow down the production of new proteins and reduce muscle growth.
Eight healthy physically active male subjects (age 21 years old, body mass 79 kg, breathing power, maximum leg lift strength: 104 kg) who had been exercising regularly for several months volunteered for this study.
The study employed a randomized counter-balanced, cross-over design in which each subject completed various types of high-intensity exercise with either post-exercise drink of carbs and alcohol, or just protein on three separate occasions.
Resistance exercise consisted of eight sets of five repetitions at 80% of their maximum strength.
After completion of the final set, subjects rested for 5 min before commencing 30 minutes of steady cycling.
Upon completion, subjects rested on the bike for 2 min before undertaking 10 x 30 seconds of high-intensity intervals at 110% of personal peak output, with 30 s active recovery (∼50% of PPO) between each work bout.
After exercise, they had either a protein drink or an energy drink.
Furthermore, a carbohydrate-based meal (1.5 g·kg−1 BM) was consumed ∼2 h post-exercise, immediately after the muscle biopsy, according to recommendations for post-exercise glycogen recovery [24].
8 hours is a recovery time as well as the period during which blood alcohol levels remain high for a while after the event, blood alcohol levels remain high
The alcohol ingestion protocol (1.5 g·kg−1 BM; 12±2 standard drinks) began 1 h post-exercise and was consumed in 6 equal volumes of 1 part vodka (∼60 mL) to four parts orange juice (∼240 mL, 1.8 g CHO·kg−1 BM) during a 3 h period.
For the PRO condition, orange juice was consumed with a matched volume of water in place of the alcohol.
Subjects drank the beverages every 30 mins.
Blood, cell signaling and mRNA data were analyzed by two-way ANOVA (two factor: time × treatment) with repeated measures and myofibrillar protein synthesis was analyzed by one-way ANOVA with repeated measures.
The first novel finding of this study was that muscle protein synthesis following mixed resistance and high-intensity exercise, designed to mimic the metabolic profile of many team sports, were impaired during the early (8 h) recovery phase by the ingestion of large amounts of alcohol.
These outcomes were clearly noticeable after drinking, makes it harder to recover
However, a second finding was that even when protein was consumed in amounts shown to be optimally effective to stimulate MPS [8] during post-exercise recovery, the intake of alcohol reduced MPS by ∼24%, representing only a partial ‘rescue’ of the body's natural healing process compared with protein alone.
The mTORC1 is a central node for integrating nutrient (i.e. amino acid) and signals from exercise [31], [32].
In conclusion, the current research provide the novel observation that alcohol impairs the response of muscle tissue in exercise recovery despite a good diet.
The amount of alcohol by athletes.
However, published reports suggest intakes of some individuals can be significantly greater [9], [50], which is of concern for many reasons related to health and safety [13].
It has been hard to look for information about alcohol and sports performance that appeals to athletes
Given the need to promote protein synthesis that underpins adaptation, repair and regeneration of skeletal muscle the results of the current study provide clear evidence of impaired recovery when alcohol is consumed after resistance and high-intensity exercise even in the presence of optimal nutritional conditions.
We propose our data is of great importance to athletes and coaches.
Our findings provide a research base for a message of moderation in alcohol intake to promote recovery after exercise with the potential to affect sports practices.
In this paper we revisit a topic originally discussed in 1955, the lack of direct evidence that exercise builds muscle strength.
To this day, long-term adaptations in strength are thought to be primarily contingent on changes in muscle size.
a lot of attention has been placed on programs designed to allow for building both muscle size and strength.
However, the conclusion that a change in muscle size affects a change in strength is surprisingly based on a small amount of evidence.
We suggest that these changes may be completely separate phenomena based on: (1) the change in muscle size doesn't directly match the change in muscle strength after training; (2) the loss of muscle mass with detraining, yet a maintenance of muscle strength; and (3) the similar muscle growth between low-load and high-load resistance training, yet divergent results in strength.
It helps to grow muscles at low intensity.
Doing it with low intensity and blood flow results in muscle growth in just a few weeks.
A typical exercise prescription calls for 3 to 5 sets when you're too tired with short rest periods.
The metabolic buildup causes positive physiologic reactions, specifically a rise in growth hormone that is higher than levels found with higher intensities.
Occlusion training is applicable for those who are unable to sustain high loads due to joint pain, recovery patients, cardiac rehabilitation, athletes with limited training capacity, and astronauts.
Studies show exercise has minimal effect on skeletal muscle size.
We and others have demonstrated that exercise acutely and chronically uses protein more efficiently and leads to muscle growth.
These findings promote an opposite view by providing novel perspective on muscle mass regulation and insight into ways to prevent muscle loss in people at risk of muscle loss.
Stretch training is widely used in a variety of fitness-related capacities such as increasing joint range of motion, preventing muscle stiffness and alleviating injuries.
Moreover, some researches indicate that stretch training may induce muscle hypertrophy; however, studies on the topic have been primarily relegated to animal and in vitro models.
The purpose of this brief review was to check if stretch training really works.
Of the 10 studies identified, 3 observed some significantly positive effects of stretch training on muscle structure.
Intriguingly, in these studies, the stretching was carried out with an apparatus that aided in its performance, or with an external overload.
5 studies on stretching and weightlifting that showed enhanced muscle growth.
In conclusion, passive, low-intensity stretch does not appear to affect muscle growth; when stretching is loaded or done between contractions, it may lead to muscle growth.
Cycle training is widely performed as a major part of any exercise program seeking to improve aerobic capacity and cardiovascular health.
However, the effect of cycle training on muscle size and strength gain still requires further insight, even though it is known that professional cyclists display larger muscle size compared to controls.
Therefore, the purpose of this review is to discuss the effects of cycling on muscle strength and the ways to increase muscle size with cycling.
It is plausible that cycle training requires a longer period to significantly increase muscle size compared to typical resistance training due to a much slower hypertrophy rate.
Cycle training induces muscle hypertrophy similarly between young and older age groups, while strength gain seems to favor older adults, which is better for older adults to improve muscle quality compared to young adults.
For young adults, more intense cycling may be required to achieve strength gains.
It also appears that muscle hypertrophy induced by cycle training results from the positive changes in muscle protein balance
Resistance training is the most effective method to increase muscle mass.
It also helps health.
Although it is deemed safe and of clinical relevance for treating and preventing a vast number of diseases, a time-efficient and minimal dose of exercise has been the focus of a great number of research studies.
Similarly, a relationship between dose and response that rises and then falls has been hypothesized to exist.
However, the majority of available evidence supports a clear dose-response relationship between resistance training volume and physiological responses, such as muscle hypertrophy and health outcomes.
There is little data to support the U-shaped response.
The overarching principle argued herein is that volume is the most easily modifiable variable that has the most evidenced-based response with important repercussions, be these muscle hypertrophy or health-related outcomes.
Although the effects of short versus long inter-set rest intervals in resistance training on muscle growth have been investigated in several studies, the findings are equivocal and the practical implications remain unclear.
It is shown that short breaks can help get stronger.
Novel findings involving trained participants using measures sensitive to detect changes in muscle hypertrophy suggest a possible advantage for the use of long rest intervals to elicit hypertrophic effects.
More research is needed to compare these two approaches. However, there is a lack of similar studies.
Memory is a process in which information is stored in the brain.
For animals, it happens only in the brain.
This review describes a memory system in muscles in which muscle growth is 'remembered' such that a muscle fibre that grew before, can regain its mass quickly.
A new cell biological model based on the literature, by the best methods for finding myonuclei, can explain this phenomenon.
According to this model, previously untrained fibres recruit myonuclei from activated satellite cells before hypertrophic growth.
Even if subjected to severe muscle wasting, muscle cell nuclei are preserved, muscle cell nuclei stay safe in weak muscles.
Fibres that have more myonuclei grow faster when subjected to overload exercise, thus the nuclei represent an important indicator of previous strength.
This memory might be very long lasting in humans, myonuclei last for a long time.
Muscle cells are harder to repair in older people, and if the long-lasting muscle memory also exists in humans, one should consider early strength training as a public health advice.
It is thought that eating small, frequent meals enhances fat loss and helps to achieve better weight maintenance.
Several observational studies lend support to this hypothesis, with a negative relationship between eating and weight.
The purpose of this review is to present and discuss a study that evaluated eating frequency and body weight, including statistical analysis.
Feeding frequency was positively associated with weight loss and body fat percentage led to increased muscle mass.
However, sensitivity analysis of the data showed that the positive findings were the product of a single study, casting doubt as to whether more frequent meals confer beneficial effects on body composition.
In conclusion, although the study found that eating more often may be beneficial for weight and body shape, these findings need to be carefully considered.
Inactive adults experience a 3% to 8% loss of muscle mass per decade, accompanied by a decrease in metabolic rate and fat accumulation.
Ten weeks of resistance training may increase lean weight by 1.4 kg, increase metabolism, and reduce fat weight by 1.8 kg.
Benefits of resistance training include better physical health, control, and self-esteem.
Resistance training may assist prevention and management of type 2 diabetes by reducing belly fat, reducing HbA1c, increasing the density of glucose transporter type 4, and improving insulin sensitivity.
Resistance training may enhance cardiovascular health, by reducing resting blood pressure, lowering bad cholesterol, and increasing high-density lipoprotein cholesterol.
Resistance training may promote bone development, Bone density increases due to exercise.
Resistance training may be effective for reducing low back pain and easing discomfort associated with arthritis and fibromyalgia and has been shown to reverse specific aging factors in skeletal muscle.
Physical activity has proved to be an effective means of preventing several diseases and improving general health.
Starting strength training is usually delayed until teenagers, especially athletes.
However, such advices seem to have a mainly anecdotal nature.
Current literature does not seem to have any particular aversion against the practice of strength training by kids and teens, with proper supervision and safety precautions.
At the same time, several studies provide consistent findings supporting the benefits of repeated, intense physical efforts in young subjects.
Improved motor skills and body composition at when they are young have been extensively documented.
Strength training is safe and healthy for kids.
Human aging results in a few changes to muscle.
Sarcopenia is the age-associated loss of muscle mass and is one of the main contributors to musculoskeletal impairments in the elderly.
Previous research has demonstrated that resistance training can attenuate muscle weakness in older people, however few articles have focused on the effects of resistance training on functional mobility.
The purpose of this systematic review was to 1) present the current state of literature regarding the effects of resistance training on functional mobility outcomes for older adults with skeletal muscle function deficits and 2) provide clinicians with practical guidelines that can be used with seniors during resistance training, or to encourage exercise.
We set forth evidence that resistance training can reduce age-related decline in movement ability, including improvements in gait speed, and fall risk reduction.
Older adults should be encouraged to participate in strength training, and should be admonished to gradually increase exercise to follow the daily activity guidelines.
Maximizing the hypertrophic response to resistance training (RT) is thought to be best achieved by adjusting the workout plan, exercise order, length of rest intervals, intensity of maximal load, and training volume.
An often overlooked thing that affects muscle growth is time spent repeating.
Duration amounts to the sum total of muscle contraction, stretching, and holding, and is predicated on the tempo at which the repetition is performed.
We conducted a review and analysis to determine whether alterations in repetition duration can amplify the hypertrophic response to RT.
Muscle growth are similar when training with from 0.5 to 8 seconds.
From a practical standpoint it would seem that a fairly wide range of repetition durations can be employed if the primary goal is to maximize muscle growth.
Findings suggest that training at slow pace is not effective for building muscle, there's not enough research.
Recovery from exercise refers to the time period between the end of a bout of exercise and the subsequent return to a resting or recovered state.
It also refers to effects after exercise that are distinct from the resting state.
Recovery of the cardiovascular system after exercise occurs over time, many things change over time.
Some of these changes may be necessary for exercise adaptation, yet some can lead to cardiovascular instability during recovery.
these changes may provide insight into when it's ready for more training after rest.
This review focuses on most observed changes in blood flow and the underlying causes that drive cardiovascular recovery and will highlight how they differ following resistance and aerobic exercise.
Primary emphasis will be placed on the hypotensive effect of aerobic and resistance exercise and associated mechanisms that have clinical relevance, but if left unchecked, can progress to symptomatic hypotension and syncope.
Finally, we focus on the practical application of this information to improve recovery or avoid problems.
We will explore appropriate field measures, and discuss how these measures can aid training.
